    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-06T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-06T07:00:00-05:00" n="874"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d874">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">681.003/161: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-06T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >March 6, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 7—9 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>96. Embassy’s telegram 27, January 21, 6 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Foreign Office states it is in receipt of a further formal request from
                        the Spanish Embassy that Great Britain relinquish its extraterritorial
                        rights in the Spanish Zone of Morocco and would be grateful if it might be
                        informed whether the Department has received a similar request.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Foreign Office had not formulated a reply and proposes “to temporize” but
                        mentioned that though it had no present intention of giving up those rights
                        it assumed “they probably can’t be held forever”.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Foreign Office thought that since we were in the same position, possible
                        concerted action seemed indicated and desirable, and Foreign Office would be
                        interested in any views the Department might wish to convey.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>The Embassy mentioned our non-recognition of the Spanish Protectorate as
                        having a possible bearing in the matter, and promised to communicate with
                        the Department by telegraph.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
